Security sources in Plateau State said N600,000 was paid as ransom tosecure the release of Igwebuike Amilia Nkechi, a corps member servingin Jos, the state capital.One of the security sources, who was part of the investigation, toldDaily Trust that Nkechi’s ransom was raised by her father.He said the corps member, with registration number PL/19B/1423 andattached to the Jos North Local Government secretariat, was releasedalongside another victim whose friends had raised N300,000 to securehis freedom.Nkechi was abducted from her home in the early hours of Monday.Using her phone, her abductors reached out to her family members inRivers and Delta states, demanding a ransom of N5 million for herrelease.However, the police said a joint operation by the police, StateSecurity Services and Operation Safe Haven, led to the corps member’srelease on Monday night.The police denied any knowledge of ransom being paid.